INSERT INTO c_content_master VALUES("88","Youths and Crime","<h3>\n	YOUTH OFFICE:</h3>\n<h4>\n	INTRODUCTION</h4>\n<p>\n	In 2008, the Botswana Police Service established the Youth Office. Its main objective being to mainstream Youth Work in the organization, establish programmes that will address internal and external youth challenges.</p>\n<p>\n	We have Youth Focal Person in all Police Stations and Districts to assist youth.</p>\n<p>\n	The programmes that are currently available are the establishment of anticrime clubs, sports and drama groups. These initiatives assist youths with something to do with their time as idling can lead to mischief.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>\n	CRIME PREVENTION AND SAFETY TIPS</h3>\n<h4>\n	FOR CHILDREN AND YOUTHS.</h4>\n<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\n	<li>\n		Do not go to strangers, accept anything from them or talk to them.</li>\n	<li>\n		When at home do not open the door to strangers. Do not tell a person over a phone call that you are alone, in case of an emergency call 999.</li>\n	<li>\n		Do not allow anyone to touch you in a way that you do not like, &ldquo;Say NO&rdquo; and inform an adult you trust or a police officer.</li>\n	<li>\n		Say NO to drugs/alcohol and substances such as marijuana, cocaine, heroin, methamphetamines. They can endanger your health and it is also illegal to possess/use them.</li>\n	<li>\n		Beware of human trafficking especially children and young women. Do not accept any offer of scholarship or job opportunity from a stranger check its authencity before accepting the offer.</li>\n	<li>\n		If you know someone who has been trafficked or you find yourself in such a situation report to the nearest police Station.</li>\n	<li>\n		Let your parent(s) or guardian(s) know where you are going and when you will be back.</li>\n	<li>\n		Do not play in the street alone, play in a group where it is safe.</li>\n	<li>\n		Obey all road signs/traffic lights, cross where there is a pedestrian crossing or when it is safe to do so.</li>\n</ul>\n","Youths and Crime","mcms","68","2017-11-14","","Active","","bps-content.php?cid=88","","","19:59:32","0","","","");
INSERT INTO c_content_master VALUES("89","Crime Trends and Statistics","<h3>\n	POLICE WEEKLY CRIME REPORT FROM 21/03/2011 TO 27/03/2011</h3>\n<p>\n	The police have noticed with concern the tendency by some bus and truck drivers who drive beyond permitted maximum speed. During the week under review, 40 bus and truck drivers were charged for over-speeding restricted vehicles.</p>\n<p>\n	The police would like to remind bus and truck drivers that the permitted maximum speed still remains 100 kilometers per an hour for such vehicles, but they are also to obey the restricted 60 or 80 kilometres per hour for built up areas.</p>\n<p>\n	Meanwhile, 350 road accidents were recorded nationwide, from which nine people lost their lives, 33 were seriously injured while 50 escaped with minor injuries. From the nine people who lost their lives, four were pedestrians and one cyclist.</p>\n<p>\n	In one incident, two women lost their lives when two motor vehicles, a Corolla and an Isuzu collided along Sekgoma road at Tsodilo Junior Secondary School junction in Maun. During the process, two women aged 16 and 24 years who were beside the road were struck by a Corolla, which is said to have gone out of control. The driver of the Corolla is likely to be charged for causing death by reckless driving.</p>\n<p>\n	The police in Tlokweng are investigating the death of an 82 year-old man of Tlokweng village. The old man was cycling on the shoulder of the road when a 54 year-old man apparently lost control of his motor vehicle and knocked the cyclist. The driver is likely to face a charge of causing death by reckless driving.</p>\n<p>\n	The police would therefore like to urge drivers to observe road signs and drive within the stipulated speed. The police preliminary investigations show that most of the fatalities were caused by failure to obey road signs and driving without due care and attention.</p>\n<h3>\n	CURRENT WEEKLY CASES RECORDED</h3>\n<h3>\n	PENAL CODE OFFENCES</h3>\n<