INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("181","Performance Management Coordination","<h3>PERFROMANCE MANEGEMENT SYSTEMS</h3>\n<p>The Branch which implements public service reform programs such as Work Improvement Teams (WITS), Performance Based Rewards System (PBRS), Systems Thinking, and Balance Score Card (BSC). The Branch has three units of Research and Development, Reforms and Public Relations.</p>\n<h3>1 Research</h3>\n<p>The unit conducts research on various policing issues, and provides findings to inform strategic decision making on crime.</p>\n<h3>2 Reforms</h3>\n<p>The Unit manages the change and productivity agenda of the organization through continuous improvement of process (PMS, WITS, Balance Score Card) and training police personnel in all strategic management processes.</p>\n<h3>3 Public Relations</h3>\n<p>As the organization&rsquo;s mouth piece, the Unit keeps the public informed about the BPS activities and services. It maintains beneficial relationships between the organization and its various publics with its publicity, promotions, advertising, research and media relations. Its major sections include Radio and Television, Publications as well as Research and Information.</p>\n<h3><em>3.1 Radio and Television</em></h3>\n<p>Radio and Television produces television programs (Itshireletse) and radio programs (Crime File) for broadcasting on Botswana Television and Radio Botswana.</p>\n<h3><em>3.2 Publications</em></h3>\n<p>The section produces publications such as the Police Magazine, billboards, posters, print adverts, brochures and banners that carry publicity materials.</p>\n<h3><em>3.3 Information and Research </em></h3>\n<p>Information and Research compiles and present factual or statistical information as requested by customers to support their stories, reports and studies. It also conducts audience surveys on its publicity programs to formulate messages that appeal specifically to targeted audiences.</p>\n<p>For more information about the Public Relations Unit, contact the Public Relations Officer at 3605439, 73102686 or email to police@gov.bw.</p>","Performance Management Coordination","mcms","179","2011-02-04","","","","bps-content.php?cid=181","","","14:24:55","0","0","","");
INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("144","Stock  Theft","<p>Stealing of stock usually is committed by herd boys or syndicates, incidents of stock are more common in areas that are close to urban centres where there are lucrative markets for beef. Criminals, who operate in syndicates, re-brand stolen cattle to defraud original owners.</p>\n\n<h3>A lot of livestock is stolen due to the following reasons:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Livestock left astray.</li>\n<li>Livestock left unbranded and not earmarked</li>\n<li>The responsibility is left solely with herd boys</li>\n<li>Late or failure to pay herd boys accordingly</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Farmers are encouraged to form up into clusters so as to intensify the fight against stock theft. Moreover, they are encouraged to take a leading role in security of their livestock.</p>\n<h3>NB: The public is urged to report to the police people they suspect to be operating livestock criminal syndicates and ascertain the authenticity of any livestock before purchasing them.</h3>","Stock  Theft","mcms","2","2011-02-04","","Active","","bps-content.php?cid=144","","","13:50:31","0","0","","");
INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("145","Habit Forming Drugs","<h3>The most common drugs in Botswana are:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Dagga remains the most abused illicit or illegal drug in Botswana due to its easy availability.</li>\n<li>Cocaine is the second placed abused drug with rock or crack cocaine being the most abused drug.</li>\n<li>Ecstasy</li>\n<li>Alcohol</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Legal implications of drugs abuse</h3>\n<p>A person who is convicted under the Drugs and Related Substances Act No. 18 of 1992 will in his/her whole lifetime have a Criminal Record which may deter him/her from being employed by any organization.</p>\n<p>There is also likely hood of imprisonment thereby spending time which someone could have developed himself to better his/her life as the penalties are so stiff.</p>\n<p>A person arrested for possession of dagga weighing less than 60 grams may find himself or herself in jail for a period not exceeding 3 years and a fine of P1000.00.</p>\n<p>A person arrested for possession of dagga weighing more than 60 grams may find himself or herself in jail for a period of not more than 5 years and to a fine of not less than P1500.00 or not more than P5000.00.</p>\n<p>A person who deals (sells, cultivate, import, manufacture etc) dagga may find himself or herself in jail for a period of not less 5 years or not more than 10 years and to fine of not less than P7000.00. whilst to cocaine, ecstasy, mandrax and other related drugs can be jailed for a period not less than 10 years or more than 15 years and to a fine of not less than P15000.00.</p>\n<h3>Social implications</h3>\n<strong>Social implications of drug abuse in both \"children and adults\", may result in:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Expulsion from work or school</li>\n<li>Sale of valuables from home to finance purchases of drugs</li>\n<li>Children drop out of school</li>\n<li>Road accidents</li>\n<li>Kidnapping of women and gang rapist.</li>\n<li>Women and child abuse. etc:</li>\n</ul>","Habit Forming Drugs, Trade and Liquor","mcms","2","2011-02-04","","Active","","bps-content.php?cid=145","","","13:51:48","0","0","","");
INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("146","Trade and Liquor","<p>According to the Statutory Instrument No. 23 of 2008 which commenced on the 1st April 2008, provides for the establishment of liquor control authorities to provide powers, duties and functions and provide comprehensive regulations of trade and liquor in Botswana.</p>\n\n<h3>Operation times for Bar</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Monday to Thursday from 1400 hours to 2200 hours, </li>\n<li>Friday to Saturday from 1200 hours to 2300 hours, and </li>\n<li>Sunday and public Holidays from 1500 hours to 2200 hours.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Operation times for Bottle Stores</h3>\n\n<ul><li>Monday to Saturday from 1000 hours to 1900 hours, </li></ul>\n\n<h3>Operation times for Clubs</h3>\n\n<ul><li>Monday to Thursday from 1400 hours to 2200 hours, </li>\n<li>Friday to Saturday from 1200 hours to 2300 hours, and </li>\n<li>Sunday and public Holidays from 1500 hours to 2200 hours.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Operation times discotheque/Night club</h3>\n\n<ul><li>Monday to Thursday from 1900 hours to 0000 hours, </li>\n<li>Friday to Saturday from 1900 hours to 0200 hours, and </li>\n<li>Sunday and public Holidays from 1500 hours to 2200 hours.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>TEMPORARY LIQUOR LICENSE</h3>\n\n<p>It is an authorization permitting the holder to sell intoxicating liquor at a public place for consumption at such place for a period not exceeding 90 days.</p>\n\n<table width=\"100%\">\n<tr><td>Trade Fair</td><td>Monday to Saturday</td><td>1200 - 1800 hours</td><tr>\n<tr><td>Festivals</td><td>Monday to Saturday</td><td>1400 - 0000 hours</td><tr>\n<tr><td>Picnics</td><td>Monday to Saturday</td><td>1200 - 1900 hours</td><tr>\n<tr><td>Other public activities</td><td>Monday to Saturday</td><td>1400 - 0000 hours</td><tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>For More Information click here <a href=\"http://www.laws.gov.bw\"><strong>(http://www.laws.gov.bw)</strong></a></p>","Victims and Witnesses Support","mcms","2","2011-02-04","","Active","","bps-content.php?cid=146","","","13:53:07","0","0","","");
INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("465","Home","<h3>SAchin</h3>\n<p>The Service shall be employed in and throughout Botswana to protect life and property, prevent and detect crime, repress internal disturbances, maintain security and public tranquillity, apprehend offenders, bring offenders to justice, duly enforce all written laws with which it is directly charged and generally maintain the peace (Botswana Police Act, Cap 21:01, section 6).</p>\n<h3>1 Our Vision:</h3>\n<p><strong>To be a law enforcement agency of repute.</strong></p>\n<p>Aspiration to provide a dignified service worthy of honour, a service that value relations with members of the community and treats customers with due respect</p>\n<h3>2 Our Mission:</h3>\n<p>To provide a professional policing service in partnership with the community</p>\n<p>A service characterised by a high level of skill, competence, speed and attention to any emerging policing challenges, and that recognizes community participation for better prevention and detection of crime.</p>\n<h3>3 Our Core Values</h3>\n<p><strong>Botho:</strong></p>\n<p>A service characterized by humility, dignity, courtesy and respect for customers, regardless of their status in life.</p>\n<p><strong>Excellence</strong></p>\n<p>An acceptable level of accuracy on all services provided to customers.</p>\n<p><strong>Integrity</strong></p>\n<p>Displaying ethical behavior that recognizes the need for confidentiality, respect for human rights and good practice</p>\n<p><strong>Team work</strong></p>\n<p>A service characterized by consultation, collective responsibility and support for each other.</p>","Welcome to Botswana Police Service","mcms","26","2011-04-12","","Active","","bps-content.php?cid=465","","","12:38:36","26","0","","");
