INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("142","Violent and Intrusive Crime","<p><strong>Violent and Intrusive Crimes</strong></p>\n<p>In cases of Armed Robberies, Robberies and their attempts  people are attacked on the streets especially in dark areas. Occasionally  business community is targeted and robbed large sum of money after being  threatened with dangerous weapons.</p>\n<p>People are advised to avoid dark areas and also to avoid  going un-accompanied during the night. The business community is advised to  always secure their premises by hiring reputable security services and  installing CCTV.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>","Violent and Intrusive Crime","mcms","2","2011-02-04","","Active","","bps-content.php?cid=142","","","13:48:20","0","0","","");
INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("143","Sexual Offences","<p>Sexual offences of concern are rape, defilement, indecent assault and incest. These are usually committed by friends or close relatives. There are few cases where these offences are committed by unknown people. Of the above offences, rape is the most common. Perpetrators sometimes date victims to entertainment places and later rape them. Due to excessive alcohol consumption, some victims realize they have been raped when they wake up the following day. As for defilement, young girls are enticed with money or valuable items to consent to sexual acts.</p> \n<h3>Reporting rape</h3>\n<p>The incident should be immediately reported to the police. The sooner an incident is reported to the police the more forensic evidence can be collected, and this may help secure a conviction.</p><br/>\n\n<h3>Advantages of reporting rape</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>An opportunity to present your side of the story.</li>\n<li>The attacker may be prosecuted.</li>\n<li>Reporting a frequent attacker may stop future attacks.</li>\n<li>The victim may receive medical assistance in time.</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n<h3>NB: Reporting an incident does not mean the attacker will be prosecuted.</h3>\n\n<h3>Police Procedures regarding rape</h3>\n<p>All police investigations start with the collection of forensic evidence. These tests are done by taking swabs from any part of your body that the assailant came in contact with. It is important that you do not do any of the following before the swabs are taken:</p>\n\nDo not wash<br/>\nDo not change your clothes<br/> \n\n","Sexual Offences","mcms","2","2011-02-04","","Active","","bps-content.php?cid=143","","","13:49:30","0","0","","");
INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("378","BPS Strategic Elements","<h3>MANDATE</h3>\n<p>The BPS shall be employed  in and throughout Botswana to protect life and property, prevent and detect  crime, repress internal disturbances, maintain security and public  tranquillity, apprehend offenders, bring offenders to justice, duly enforce all  written laws with which it is directly charged and generally maintain the peace (Botswana Police Act,  Cap 21:01, section 6).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Our Vision:</h3>\n<h3>To be a law enforcement agency of repute</h3>\n<p>Aspiration to provide a dignified service worthy of honour, a service that value relations with members of the community and treats customers with due respect</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Our Mission:</h3>\n<h3>To provide a professional policing service in partnership with the community</h3>\n<p>A<strong> </strong>service characterised by a high level of  skill, competence, speed and attention to any emerging policing challenges, and  that recognizes community participation for better prevention and detection of  crime.&nbsp; <strong> </strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Our Core Values</h3>\n<p><strong>&bull; Botho: </strong><br />\nA service characterized by humility, dignity, courtesy and respect  for customers, regardless of their status in life.</p>\n<p><strong>&bull; Excellence </strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />\nAn acceptable level of accuracy on all services provided to  customers.</p>\n<p><strong>&bull; Integrity &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><br />\nDisplaying ethical behavior that recognizes the need for  confidentiality, respect for human rights and good practice</p>\n<p><strong>&bull; Team work</strong><br />\nA service characterized by consultation,  collective responsibility and support for each other. <strong> </strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","BPS Strategic Elements","mcms","1","2011-03-14","","Active","","bps-content.php?cid=378","","","08:43:49","0","0","","");
INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("129","Performance Management Coordination","<p>The Branch which implements public service reform programs such as Work Improvement Teams (WITS), Performance Based Rewards System (PBRS), Systems Thinking, and Balance Score Card (BSC). The Branch has three units of Research and Development, Reforms and Public Relations.<br />\n<br />\n3.1 Research<br />\n&nbsp;The unit conducts research on various policing issues, and provides findings to inform strategic decision making on crime. <br />\n3.2 Reforms <br />\nThe Unit manages the change and productivity agenda of the organization through continuous improvement of process (PMS, WITS, Balance Score Card) and training police personnel in all strategic management processes. <br />\n3.3 Public Relations&nbsp; <br />\n<br />\nAs the organization&rsquo;s mouth piece, the Unit keeps the public informed about the BPS activities and services. It maintains beneficial relationships between the organization and its various publics with its publicity, promotions, advertising, research and media relations. Its major sections include Radio and Television, Publications as well as Research and Information. <br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n3.3.1 Radio and Television<br />\n<br />\nRadio and Television produces television programs (Itshireletse) and radio programs (Crime File) for broadcasting on Botswana Television and Radio Botswana.<br />\n<br />\n3.3.2 Publications<br />\n<br />\nThe section produces publications such as the Police Magazine, billboards, posters, print adverts, brochures and banners that carry publicity materials.<br />\n<br />\n3.3.3 Information and Research <br />\n<br />\nInformation and Research compiles and present factual or statistical information as requested by customers to support their stories, reports and studies. It also conducts audience surveys on its publicity programs to formulate messages that appeal specifically to targeted audiences.&nbsp; <br />\n<br />\nFor more information about the Public Relations Unit, contact the Public Relations Officer at 3605439, 73102686 or email to police@gov.bw.</p>","Performance Management Coordination","mcms","93","2011-02-04","","","","bps-content.php?cid=129","","","11:46:14","113","0","","");
INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("130","Department of Management Services","<p>DEPARTMENTAL MANAGEMENT SERVICES:<br />\nDepartmental Management Services Branch manages, directs and develops a diverse range of key corporate management functions and services which include Finance, Development, Legal Services, Training, Stores, Administration and Human Resources Management for the entire Botswana Police Service to enhance and accelerate the growth of a pool of experienced managers to meet medium and long term organisational development demands. The Units under it are as follows together with its mandates:-<br />\n<br />\n1.HUMAN RESOURCES:<br />\nThe Human Resources Unit is ensuring effective administration of the human resources policies, procedures and programs to the organisation in the areas of training and development, recruitment and selection, performance management, succession planning and to provide advisory support to line management and staff to facilitate and enhance a constructive and positive work environment in order to meet organizational objectives. It also develops position profiles and career development paths to attract and retain suitably qualified and experienced staff.<br />\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Key functions:-<br />\nRecruitment and selection<br />\nRedundancy<br />\nPromotions and Transfers<br />\nIndustrial and Employee Relations<br />\nRecord keeping of all personal data<br />\nEmployee benefits and compensation<br />\nConfidential advice to internal customer in relation to problems at work<br />\nCareer development and succession planning<br />\nCompetency Mapping (To identify and describe competencies that are most critical to success in a work situation or work role.)<br />\nManpower Planning<br />\nPerformance Appraisal<br />\nFor further information contact: <br />\nHuman Resources Unit<br />\nBotswana Police Service<br />\nPhone: 3951161/3910051/3605513//3605454&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />\nFax: 3910081<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; OCCUPATIONAL HEALTH AND SAFETY:<br />\nBringing health to work<br />\nThe Occupational Health, Safety, Chaplaincy and Social Welfare (OHSCSW) Unit of the Botswana Police Service has been established to create a positive healthy, safe, spiritually and psychosocially supportive work environment for the employees. Having been established initially as the HIV/AIDS Coordinating Unit in 2003, the Unit also attended to all health and social welfare issues of employees. It was then reconstituted into the OHSCSW in 2006 in order to address all human life issues in the workplace holistically. <br />\n<br />\nThe Botswana Police Service Occupational Health Safety Chaplaincy &amp; Social Welfare (OHSCSW) concept strives to eliminate that which challenges the mental, physical and social state. Thus, what need to be taken care of proactively are the body, mind and soul. These therefore calls for taking care of the broader social and domestic dynamics of employees such as those related to personal and family life.&nbsp; The individual worker from this view point is therefore considered a &ldquo;system nested&rdquo; within a person-situation environment operating at different levels such as the physical-biological, cognitive, emotion, action and reaction style of functioning. Wellness is an active process of becoming aware of and making choices towards a healthy and productive lifestyle in the workplace. <br />\n<br />\nThe Botswana Police Service is constantly interacting with its customers. Some of the customers may have social problems whilst others are survivors/victims of crime. Where possible, customers who need counseling may be assisted accordingly. This therefore has necessitated the need to strengthen the psychosocial support component of the OHSCSW Unit. In view of the shortage of qualified professionals such as social workers and psychologists, the organization took a deliberate move to build the capacity of lay-counselors to complement the services provided for by skilled professional helpers. <br />\n<br />\nThe implementation of the OHSCSW programmes is achieved through established structures in all police establishments and these are:<br />\nOHSCSW Advisory Committee at national level <br />\nOHSCSW Coordinating Unit - Police Headquarters<br />\nBranch Focal Persons which form the OHSCSW Advisory Committee.<br />\nOHSCSW officers at division level.<br />\nOHSCSW workplace committees at district and station levels.<br />\nHealth and Safety assistants who also play a dual of HIV/AIDS peer educators at station level.<br />\nSocial Work Assistants also perform as HIV/AIDS Counsellors at station level<br />\n&nbsp;Chaplain assistants at station level.<br />\n<br />\nMAJOR COMPONENTS OF THE OHSCSW PROGRAMME<br />\n1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HIV/AIDS Prevention, Care and Support<br />\n<br />\nThe Botswana Police Service HIV/AIDS Mission Statement is to ensure that all its employees and their families are well informed and encouraged to take practical steps to avoid new infections and to provide adequate care and support services to the infected and affected. <br />\nThe Botswana Police Service HIV/AIDS Policy (2005) and Botswana Police Service Strategic Plan on HIV/AIDS 2003-2009 which are under review, guide implementation of the HIV/AIDS prevention, care and support programme. The focus has been on the following core initiatives;<br />\nWorkplace HIV Voluntary Counselling and Testing campaigns with assistance from Tebelopele Counselling Centres, clinics and hospitals.<br />\nCondom education and distribution.<br />\nPeer education based on the premise that HIV infection is preventable and requires change in behaviour.<br />\nPeer counselling on HIV/AIDS and social traumatic issues<br />\nMonitoring and evaluation of the programme&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />\nProduction of HIV/AIDS IEC materials which included posters, banners, leaflets, focal persons directory, etc<br />\n<br />\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Occupational Health and Safety Management<br />\nThe Botswana Police Service Occupational Health and Safety Policy (2005) which is under review, require that everyone in the workplace has some obligations to ensure the safety of themselves and others. The publication of this document demonstrates the BPS management&rsquo;s commitment in ensuring the health, safety and welfare of BPS employees. The policy outlines the responsibilities for supervisors and employees to ensure that all levels of the BPS structure have the necessary direction.<br />\nThe Occupational Health and Safety management focuses on preventing injury or illness and eliminating hazards through safety audits and risk assessment. It includes traditional health promotion activities at work which encourage overall health and wellness (eg physical activity, stress management, healthy eating, screening tests, etc). It further includes organisational health which deals with management practices and strategies that focus on culture, relationships and values within the workplace. <br />\n<br />\n3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Employee Social Welfare Management<br />\nThe Employee Social Welfare Management deals with management of all forms of stress, psychosocial trauma and abuse in order to alleviate human suffering among employees, their families and our clientele through employee assistance programmes that include among others critical incidents stress debriefing (CISD) in which all officers who would have attended any critical incident during execution of their duties in order to mitigate the impact and accelerate the returning of these officers to optimal functioning. Such incidents include any incident that has significant emotional power to overwhelm usual coping mechanisms, resulting in serious line of duty injuries, or accidental and line of duty deaths. These include fatal road accidents, disastrous incidents such as plane crash, drowning, some suicides, murder, postmortems, etc. It shall be the duty of the station commander or anybody in charge of the station at the material time to ensure that such services are provided. <br />\n4)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Chaplaincy Programme<br />\nThe Chaplaincy programme has been introduced to provide spiritual guidance and support to BPS employees and their dependents, regardless of their religious affiliation. Our mission in this programme is to provide opportunities for spiritual and moral growth of the Botswana Police Service employees and their dependents with a view to create a ministry of care, support and presence to the employees. Through the Return-to-work programme, the Chaplaincy Section facilitates the earliest possible return of ill employees to productive work within their physical capabilities. This is achieved through modified duty allocated to the individual as part of the employee normal duties are changed to accommodate temporary physical and mental limitations. Based on this account, Chaplain and Chaplain Assistants have the responsibility to visit and pray with all employees who are either confined to the hospital or are on a long sick leave within their areas of operation. <br />\nFor further information contact: <br />\nOccupational Health, Safety, Chaplaincy and Social Welfare Unit<br />\nBotswana Police Service<br />\nPhone: 3951161/3622044/3622114/3622253&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />\nFax: 3973723<br />\n<br />\n3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; SALARIES AND WELFARE:<br />\nThe Unit is responsible for:- <br />\nThe day to day functions of the Salaries Unit &amp; ensures that the Botswana Police Service Payroll is effectively maintained. Also supervises the management of the Police Savings &amp; Loan Guarantee Scheme.<br />\nInitiates pay and benefits surveys and constantly monitors group policies and practices to ensure competitiveness<br />\nProcesses workman&rsquo;s compensation claims in the event of employee accidents to expedite the payment claims.<br />\nPrepares Casualty Returns for updating of the payroll to ensure that Industrial Class Employees are properly paid wages, allowances and deductions are made.<br />\nPrepares Casualty Returns for Housing benefit Tax to ensure that employees&rsquo; remunerations and deductions are done accordingly.<br />\n4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEGAL SERVICES:<br />\nThe Legal Services Unit mandate is to provide legal and administrative advice to BPS. In so doing the Unit performs the under listed duties:-<br />\nHandling of complaints by members of the public against the police<br />\nHandling of Affidavits from the Attorney General.<br />\nDealing with personnel files on legal/administrative issues.<br />\nProcurement and distribution of legal materials within the organisation.<br />\nAdvising the organisation on contractual issues.<br />\nHandling of claims against the police and instructing the Attorney General accordingly.<br />\n5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; INTERNAL AFFAIRS:<br />\nThe Unit is responsible for the day-to-day administration duties of the branch and ensuring that the integrity of the Botswana Police Service is maintained through a system of internal discipline where fairness and justice are assured by an objective and impartial investigation and review of cases.<br />\n<br />\n6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; YOUTH OFFICE:<br />\nINTRODUCTION<br />\n<br />\nIn 2008, the Botswana Police Service established the Youth Office.&nbsp; Its main objective being to mainstream Youth Work in the organization, establish programmes that will address internal and external youth challenges.<br />\n<br />\nWe have Youth Focal Person in all Police Stations and Districts to assist youth.<br />\n<br />\nThe programmes that are currently available are the establishment of anticrime clubs, sports and drama groups.&nbsp; These initiatives assist youths with something to do with their time as idling can lead to mischief.<br />\n<br />\nCRIME PREVENTION AND SAFETY TIPS <br />\nFOR CHILDREN AND YOUTHS.<br />\n<br />\n1.Do not go to strangers, accept anything from them or talk to them.<br />\n<br />\n2.When at home do not open the door to strangers.&nbsp; Do not tell a person over a phone call that you are alone, in case of an emergency call 999.<br />\n<br />\n3.Do not allow anyone to touch you in a way that you do not like, &ldquo;Say NO&rdquo; and inform an adult you trust or a police officer.<br />\n<br />\n4.Say NO to drugs/alcohol and substances such as marijuana, cocaine, heroin, methamphetamines.&nbsp; They can endanger your health and it is also illegal to possess/use them.<br />\n<br />\n5.Beware of human trafficking especially children and young women.&nbsp; Do not accept any offer of scholarship or job opportunity from a stranger check its authencity before accepting the offer.<br />\n<br />\n6.If you know someone who has been trafficked or you find yourself in such a situation report to the nearest police Station.<br />\n<br />\n7.Let your parent(s) or guardian(s) know where you are going and when you will be back.<br />\n<br />\n8.Do not play in the street alone, play in a group where it is safe.<br />\n<br />\n9.Obey all road signs/traffic lights, cross where there is a pedestrian crossing or when it is safe to do so.<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ADMINISTRATION:<br />\nIs responsible for providing administrative function to the organisation ensuring that relevant information is properly disseminated to both internal and external stakeholders as well as advising management on policy issues.<br />\n<br />\n8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; TRAINING:<br />\nTo interpret, implement, coordinate, review and evaluate training and development policy in order to meet the manpower development needs of the organization.<br />\n9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PENSIONS:<br />\nThe Unit manages the day to day functions of the Pensions Unit ensuring proper administration of the Pension Fund for the Botswana Police Service in terms of the Pensions Act Cap 27:01, the General Orders, the Police Act Cap 21:01a and the New Defined Contributory Pension Fund Regulations.<br />\nFacilitates the assessment of guardianship of minor dependants of deceased officers by monitoring the communication with the legal representatives and recommendations of the guardians as per the rules of the Fund.<br />\nReceives, investigates and answers beneficiaries and member related queries.<br />\nEnsures that all officers who retire, resign and those who are dismissed complete notification forms in time to facilitate the speedy processing of benefits/pension.<br />\n<br />\n&nbsp;</p>","Department of Management Services","mcms","94","2011-02-04","","Active","","bps-content.php?cid=130","","","11:49:23","114","0","","");
