INSERT INTO c_content_master_old VALUES("392","Crime Trends and Statistics","<h3>POLICE WEEKLY CRIME REPORT FROM 21/03/2011 TO 27/03/2011</h3>\n<p>The police have noticed with concern the tendency by some bus and truck  drivers who drive beyond permitted maximum speed. During the week under review,  40 bus and truck drivers were charged for over-speeding restricted vehicles.</p>\n <p>The police would like to remind bus and truck drivers that the permitted  maximum speed still remains 100 kilometers per an hour for such vehicles, but  they are also to obey the restricted 60 or 80 kilometres per hour for built up  areas. </p>\n <p> Meanwhile, 350 road accidents were recorded nationwide, from which nine  people lost their lives, 33 were seriously injured while 50 escaped with minor  injuries. From the nine people who lost their lives, four were pedestrians and  one cyclist.</p>\n <p>In one incident, two women lost their lives when two motor vehicles, a  Corolla and an Isuzu collided along Sekgoma road at Tsodilo Junior Secondary  School junction in Maun. During the process, two women aged 16 and 24 years who  were beside the road were struck by a Corolla, which is said to have gone out  of control. The driver of the Corolla is likely to be charged for causing death  by reckless driving.</p>\n <p>The police in Tlokweng are investigating the death of an 82 year-old man  of Tlokweng village. The old man was  cycling on the shoulder of the road when a 54 year-old man apparently lost  control of his motor vehicle and knocked the cyclist. The driver is likely to  face a charge of causing death by reckless driving.</p>\n <p>The police would therefore like to urge drivers to observe road signs and  drive within the stipulated speed. The police preliminary investigations show  that most of the fatalities were caused by failure to obey road signs and  driving without due care and attention.</p>\n <h3>CURRENT WEEKLY CASES RECORDED</h3><br/>\n <h3>PENAL CODE OFFENCES </h3>